title.en: Digital Identity Description Language (DIDL) Information Model, Vocabulary, and Expression v0.1

affiliation.value: Institute for Man-Machine Interaction (MMI), RWTH Aachen University

abstract.value:
Identities are abstract concepts that represent entities within a given context. They may take various formats and serve diverse purposes. In data ecosystems, in which different participants share data and services in a secure, interoperable, and sovereign manner, identities are primarily considered for identification, authentication, and authorization. Here, identities must be represented concretely and precisely. 
Digital Identity Description Language (DIDL) is an abstract language to describe identity concepts used in data ecosystems. The core component, identity, is specialized into identifiers, credentials, and assertions, utilized in the process of authentication and authorization.

A cryptographic proof—typically a digital signature—used to validate the authenticity and integrity of a credential or assertion, often embedded in formats like JWTs, SAML assertions, or verifiable credentials.
A session-based key as a credential used for temporary authentication
A physical card with embedded integrated circuits capable of securely storing and processing data—often used for authentication, digital signatures, and secure credential storage in identity systems.
A credential that indicates something you have
A 48-bit globally unique identifier typically used to identify network interfaces (commonly known as a MAC address), assigned by IEEE to ensure uniqueness across devices.
A standardized string used to uniquely identify a resource on the Internet or a private network, encompassing both URLs and URNs.
An ITU-T Recommendation for public telephone systems that defines the format of phone numbers, typically up to 15 digits, including country codes (e.g., +1 650 555 1234).
A 128-bit value generated using specific algorithms to ensure uniqueness across time and space, commonly used to identify objects, records, or resources in software systems.
A unique hierarchical identifier used to unambiguously identify an entry in an X.500 directory, composed of attribute–value pairs
An extended version of a URI that allows the use of Unicode characters from the Universal Character Set (UCS), enabling identifiers in languages beyond ASCII.

A globally unique, cryptographically verifiable identifier that does not require a centralized registry and is designed to enable self-sovereign digital identity, see also W3C DID https://www.w3.org/TR/did-1.0/
A 64-bit globally unique identifier used to identify hardware or devices, often derived from a 48-bit MAC address and used in protocols like IPv6 for interface identifiers.

A foundational standard that specifies the implementation of the Domain Name System (DNS) — detailing message formats, query/response interactions, and resource records used for translating domain names to IP addresses.
A unique identifier designed to track individual physical objects in the supply chain using RFID technology, enabling item-level identification beyond traditional barcodes.

A standard that defines rules for the precise comparison of internationalized usernames and passwords, specifying string preparation, normalization, and case-mapping to avoid ambiguities and spoofing in authentication systems.
A standardized structure for identifying electronic mailboxes, typically in the form local-part@domain
A type of URI that not only identifies a resource but also provides a means of locating it by describing its access mechanism (e.g., https, ftp) and network location.
Random UUID with no embedded metadata, offering a high degree of uniqueness
Name-based UUID using SHA-1
Distributed Computing Environment (DCE) Security UUID
Name-based UUID using MD5
Time-based UUID
A type of URI intended to serve as a persistent, location-independent resource identifier, often used to name resources in a globally unique and stable way (e.g., urn:isbn:0451450523).
An identifier format that is specified by a standard or a protocol

A concept that represents the use of  an identifier

A biometric credential format that captures and encodes a person's unique fingerprint features—typically minutiae points—into a standardized digital representation for authentication or identification, see also IEC 19704-2
A biometric credential format that encodes the unique vocal characteristics of a person—such as pitch, tone, and rhythm—into a digital template for speaker verification or identification.
A credential that indicates something you inherently have
A accumulated assertion consists of multiple assertions
A credential format that is specified by a standard or a protocol
A token issued to an application (rather than a user) to authenticate itself when accessing APIs or services, often used in machine-to-machine (M2M) communication.
A type of access token that allows access to a resource simply by presenting the token, without requiring additional proof of identity—"whoever bears it, can use it."
A time-bound token issued by an authorization server that grants a client application permission to access protected resources on behalf of a user or itself, see also RFC 6749
A credential issued by an authorization server that allows a client to obtain a new access token without requiring the user to reauthenticate, typically used in long-lived sessions.
A time-limited, encrypted credential issued by a Kerberos Key Distribution Center (KDC) that allows a client to authenticate to services without repeatedly sending passwords.
A compact, URL-safe token format that represents claims between parties using a JSON object, digitally signed (and optionally encrypted) for secure transmission and verification.
A digital certificate that uses the X.509 public key infrastructure (PKI) standard to bind a subject's identity to a public key, and is signed by a trusted Certificate Authority (CA).

A structured XML statement issued by an Identity Provider (IdP) in a SAML 2.0 authentication exchange, containing claims (such as user identity, authentication status, and attributes) that a Service Provider (SP) can trust.
A security token issued by an OpenID Connect Provider that contains claims about the authentication of an end-user and possibly their identity attributes, typically formatted as a signed JWT.
